SIMPLE: pipit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pipit
<hw>Pip"it</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So named from its call
note.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of
small singing birds belonging to <gen>Anthus</gen> and allied genera, of
the family <fam>Motacillid⟦ae⟧</fam>. They strongly resemble the true
larks in habits, colors, and the great length of the hind claw. They
are, therefore, often called <altname>titlarks</altname>, and
<altname>pipit larks</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <stype>meadow pipit</stype> (<spn>Anthus
pratensis</spn>); the <stype>tree pipit</stype>, or tree lark
(<spn>Anthus trivialis</spn>); and the <stype>rock pipit</stype>, or sea
lark (<spn>Anthus obscurus</spn>) are well-known European species. The
common American <ex>pipit</ex>, or brown lark, is <spn>Anthus
Pensilvanicus</spn>. The Western species (<spn>Anthus Spraguei</spn>) is
called the <stype>American skylark</stype>, on account of its musical
powers.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pipkin</ent>⟦br⟧
